===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|てら}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=てら|-}}. Appears in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 {{CE}},<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2|寺}}</ref> and in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'', completed some time after 759 {{CE}}.<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|16|3822}}, text [https://web.archive.org/web/20220626150734/http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man16Yo.html#3822 here]</ref>

There are various theories regarding the ultimate derivation.
* Some sources<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref> derive Japanese ''tera'' from an ancestor of Middle {{der|ja|ko|sort=てら|졀}} (likely Baekje). This is from earlier {{m|ko|뎔||[[temple]]}} and is the nativised reading of {{ko-l|찰|刹|Buddhist temple}} below, deriving in turn from {{cog|ltc|-}} {{ltc-l|剎}}, shortened from {{ltc-l|剎多羅|[[Buddhist]] [[monastery]], [[temple]] or [[shrine]]}}, borrowed from {{cog|sa|क्षेत्र||[[land]], [[area]], [[domain]]}}, from {{der|ja|inc-pro|sort=てら|*ṭṣáytram}}, from {{der|ja|iir-pro|sort=てら|*ćšáytram}}, from {{der|ja|ine-pro|sort=てら|*tḱey-|*tḱéytrom}}.
* Other sources<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> describe Japanese ''tera'' as cognate with modern {{cog|ko|-}} {{ko-l|찰|刹|temple}}, appearing as a component in terms such as {{ko-l|선찰|禪刹|Zen temple}}, {{ko-l|사찰|寺刹|Buddhist temple}}.
* Another derivation<ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref><ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> is given as {{der|ja|pi|sort=てら|thera||[[elder]]s}} in reference to the monks.

Considering the phonetic development in Korean, the avenues for transmission of Buddhist terms to Japan, and the consistent {{m|en|temple}} sense of the Japanese term throughout recorded history, the now-obsolete {{cog|ko|뎔||temple}} may be a more likely source than {{cog|pi|thera||elders}}.

